Reading in the data: 2 pts

  1. Im sure you know that salaries often exhibit a skewed distribution.
  1. Investigate these data to see if a transformation is needed. If so, do it throughout this assignment. (Explain.) 1 pt

I am using log(salary) because it has a more symmetric distribution. WE will always have a lump of rookies at the bottom end of the scale getting the minimum salary, so no transformation fixes that. I removed these variables: number, first name, last name, college, birth city, high school, and high school city because I think they are non-informative. I plotted boxplots of birth-state and high school-state, but could see no pattern. They soak up many degrees of freedom, and think they should not be important. I left them in, but will be surprised if they get used.
I filled two NAs for Nteams with 1s, as those players had 3 and 4 years of experience.

I didnt realize which positions tend to get more money. I wonder if there is a weight by position interaction because for some positions weight is an asset, for others a detriment.

  1. Demonstrate how the step function can be used in R to do forward, backward, or stepwise variable selection. Start with a full model to use backward and for one both directions fit. Start with just one variable to use forward and another both fit. Do the four results agree? What is the best AICc fit youve found? (2 pts)

The four models all agree on a model with position, height, weight, experience, probowl, number of teams, and Heisman. Its AIC is 870.9.

  1. Read the data into SAS. Use the PROC GLMSELECT (2006?) to fit a variety of models. Refer to the example on modeling baseball salaries based on performance measures. Use forward, backward and stepwise. For at least one of these invoke stats = all and compare the different criterions favorite models. (2 pts)

Using Forward selection, PROC GLMSELECT added these terms: experience (p-value < .0001), number of teams (<0.0001), height (0.0004), and stopped before adding weight (0.24). AICcs reduced from -863 (intercept only) to -1464, -1568, and -1579 (plateaued) and all criteria agreed on this model except adjusted \(R^2\) which would add weight to get a very small increase.
With Backwards selection, the p-value approach removed Birth-State (even though it reports a small p-value of 0.004) and High-School-State (p-value = 0.42) and ends up keeping only Experience, number of teams and height. BIC, C\(_p\) and AIC as shown in the plots agree, but that models AICc is -1579 which is larger than the AICc of the model which also includes race, position, weight and weight by position interaction (AICc = -1636.4), so I think AICc likes a model much like that chosen in R.
Using stepwise selection, the algorithm only added terms and stopped at the same model as in forward selection.

setwd("/home/jimrc/classes/stat506/homework/assn4/")
fball <- read.csv("../../data/2014-NFL-Census-Shared.csv", sep = "\t", as.is=TRUE)
names(fball)
summary(fball)
fball$Nteams[c(286,336)-2] <- 1
fball <- subset(fball, AvgSalary > 1)
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
hist(fball$AvgSalary)
hist(sqrt(fball$AvgSalary))
hist(log(fball$AvgSalary))

fball$BDAY <- lubridate::ymd(fball$BDAY)
fball$POS <- factor(fball$POS)
fball$X <- NULL
fball$Race <- factor(fball$Race)
names(fball)[1] <- "team"
names(fball)[5] <- "position"
names(fball)[6:7] <- c("height","weight")
fball$team <- factor(fball$team)
fball$BirthState <- factor(fball$BirthState)
fball$HSState <- factor(fball$HSState)
fball <- fball[, -c(2:4,8,10,12,15,16)] 
fball$lsalary <- log10(fball$AvgSalary +1)
fball$Champ <- ifelse(fball$Champ=="NO",0,as.numeric(fball$Champ))
fball$Heisman  <- ifelse(fball$Heisman =="NO",0,1)
fball$AvgSalary <- NULL
par(mfrow=c(3,4))
boxplot(lsalary ~ team, fball, horizontal = TRUE, las = 1,main = "Team")
boxplot(lsalary ~ position, fball, horizontal = TRUE, las = 1, main = "Position")
plot(lsalary ~ height, fball, main = "Height")
 lines(lowess(fball$height, fball$lsalary), col = 2)
plot(lsalary ~ weight, fball, main = "Weight")
 lines(lowess(fball$weight, fball$lsalary), col = 2)
boxplot(lsalary ~ EXP, fball, horizontal = TRUE, las = 1, main = "Experience")
boxplot(lsalary ~ Race, fball, horizontal = TRUE, las = 1, main = "Race")
##boxplot(lsalary ~ BirthState, fball, horizontal = TRUE, las = 1)
##boxplot(lsalary ~ HSState, fball, horizontal = TRUE, las = 1)
boxplot(lsalary ~ ProBowler, fball, horizontal = TRUE, las = 1, main = "ProBowl")
boxplot(lsalary ~ Champ, fball, horizontal = TRUE, las = 1, main = "Championship")
boxplot(lsalary ~ Nteams, fball, horizontal = TRUE, las = 1, main = "Number of Teams")
boxplot(lsalary ~ Heisman, fball, horizontal = TRUE, las = 1, main = "Heisman")
table(fball$Heisman)
 ## write.csv(fball, file="football.csv", row.names=FALSE, quote=FALSE)
 ## I don't like Heisman (too few). Nteams is too like experience r = .4
require(ggplot2, quietly=TRUE)
qplot( x=weight,y=lsalary,data=fball)  + facet_wrap(~position) + theme_bw() ##+ geom_smooth()
fitAll <- lm(lsalary ~ . + position *weight, data = fball[,-1], subset = complete.cases(fball))
anova(fitAll)
# drop1(fitAll)
backstepFit <- step(fitAll,trace=FALSE)
rownames(anova(backstepFit))
fwdstepFit <- step( lm(lsalary ~ position, fball, subset = complete.cases(fball)), scope=list(upper=formula(fitAll)),dir="for", trace=FALSE)
rownames(anova(fwdstepFit))
stepUpstepFit  <- step( lm(lsalary ~ position, fball, subset = complete.cases(fball)), scope=list( lower = ~1, upper=formula(fitAll)),dir="both", trace = FALSE)
rownames(anova(stepUpstepFit))
stepDwnstepFit  <- step( fitAll, scope=list( lower = ~1, upper=formula(fitAll)),dir="both", trace = FALSE)
rownames(anova(stepDwnstepFit))
require(lme4, quietly=TRUE)
mixedFit <- lmer(lsalary ~ position + height +weight + EXP + ProBowler+Nteams + Heisman +(1|team), data = subset(fball, complete.cases(fball)))
anova(mixedFit,test="Chisq")
confint(mixedFit, parm = 1:2)
out1 <- round(summary(backstepFit)$coef[17:22, 1:2],3)
out2 <- round(summary(mixedFit)$coefficients[17:22, 1:2],3)
output <- matrix(c(rownames(out1), paste(out1[,1]," (",out1[,2],")",sep=""),
                  paste(out1[,1]," (",out1[,2],")",sep="")), ncol=3,
                  dimnames = list(NULL, c("Effect", "lm-Estimates", "lmer-Estimates")))
knitr::kable(output)

  ## with code chunk option:  comment=""
temp <- scan(file="football.sas", what = "a", sep = "\n")
cat(paste(temp,"\n"))
Proc import  datafile="/folders/myfolders/football.csv" 
     out=fball   dbms=dlm    replace; 
     delimiter=","; 
     getnames=YES; 
     run; 
   
  *PROC CONTENTS data = fball; 
  *RUN; 
   
  title "Forward stepwise"; 
  PROC GLMSELECT data = fball plot = criterionPanel ; 
    class position team birthstate hsstate race; 
    model lsalary = weight position weight*position  race exp nteams height birthstate hsstate/  
                    stats=all orderselect selection = forward stop = adjrsq hier=single; 
                    run; 
                     
  title "Backward Stepwise";                     
  PROC GLMSELECT data = fball plot = criterionPanel ; 
    class position team birthstate hsstate race; 
    model lsalary = weight position weight*position  race exp nteams height birthstate hsstate /  
                    stats=all orderselect selection = backward  hier=single 
                    slstay = .05; 
  run; 
   
  title "Stepwise Stepwise"; 
  PROC GLMSELECT data = fball plot = criterionPanel ; 
    class position team birthstate hsstate race; 
    model lsalary = weight position height height*position race exp nteams birthstate hsstate /  
                    stats=all orderselect selection = stepwise slentry=0.20  
                    slstay = 0.1 stop = aicc hier = single; 
  run;
